<td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Terminology</td>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Number of value sets used and the number of individual codes</td>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Value sets per phenotype definition, codes per code system</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/ocac235-T1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="tblfn1"><p>
<em>Abbreviation</em>: FHIR: Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources.</p></div></div></section></section></section></section><section id="sec12"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">RESULTS</h2>
<section id="sec13"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Metadata</h3>
<p>
<a href="#ocac235-T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a> provides metadata extracted by manually reviewing each phenotype definition. Our manually determined types align with the self-reported PheKB types, but we introduce a new type with the label “valid data.” This indicates that the phenotype definition is trying to identify patients without disqualifying data. For example, the <em>height</em> phenotype definition identifies individuals who have a valid height measurement and do not have any conditions that may impact height. We also introduce the “treatment/therapy” type, which identifies individuals who have had a specific treatment, for example, <em>bone scan utilization</em>. Finally, we describe the approach outlined for NLP implementation (if applicable).</p>
